Due to continued poor air quality conditions, we will be limiting our office hours for the remainder to this week, September 16-18.

Our school offices will be open as follows:
9:00 am - 1:00 pm for Surprise Lake Middle School, Columbia Junior High, Fife High School
10:00 am - 2:00 pm Discovery Primary, Endeavour Intermediate, Hedden Elementary

Our mobile meal program will continue on its routes both in the morning and mid-day.

With much pride, it's our honor to announce that Alice V. Hedden Elementary has been recognized for closing gaps! Schools with this award serve all students equitably and improve outcomes for all students. Washington state has re-imagined what school recognition means. State-recognized schools are highlighted yearly for closing gaps, showing growth, and demonstrating achievement!

Congratulations to the staff of Hedden Elementary for this prestigious and well-deserved award!

Find out more about Washingtonâ€™s School Recognition Program: sbe.wa.gov/schoolrecognition

post_text:
We wanted to take a moment to thank a very specific group of individuals. At the end of tomorrow's Fife Feeds distribution, our Food Services team - Toni Barnett, Deanna Corrie, Sue Allen, Lisa Jeffreys, Charity Giboney, Patricia Hunter, Claire Robertson, Mark Podesta, Diane Arndt, Maria Luciano, Elaine Phillips Smith, Teressa Hebert, Carol Walter, Sabrina Cruzan, and Sherry Andrews - will have made 55,600+ meals for children in our school district!

Not one team member has taken a single day off and together they have worked tirelessly to secure enough food to feed approximately 2,150 meals daily. Their commitment to feeding our students is remarkable! Please join us in saluting these true heroes in our midst.
#togetherweRfife

post_text: TRAFFIC ALERT: Please see the information from City of Fife, Washington below. This will impact traffic causing possible delays to our morning and afternoon school bus runs March 6-23.
shared_text:
City of Fife, Washington
February 20 at 2:47 PM Â·

Local drivers should be aware of a major I-5 ramp closure at Port of Tacoma Road in Fife from March 6-23, due to a vital cleanup project. View full details and alternate routes at https://cityoffife.org/traffic.

The cleanup is required following an accident in 2016 when a fuel truck overturned on Port of Tacoma Road. The insurance company for that truck driver is paying for the cleanup and project. The project is significant because the overturned truck leaked 7,500 gallons of fuel. Much of the contaminated soil already has been removed, but the time has come to remove the last of the contaminated soil under the roadways.

We'll be sending out several alerts leading up to the closure and during the closure, but please consider sharing this post with your friends who regularly drive this route.

Our maintenance team has been busy today preparing for next week's forecast! Please remember if we need to close school due to weather conditions, we will notify families and staff in the following ways:
1. Automated phone call to all families and staff.
2. District Website - A banner will pop up on our district website with any updates/changes to our schedule. We only post in one place online to ensure that the information is accurate and updated.
3. Via the Flash Alert app. Visit https://www.flashalert.net/signup/ to sign up. This alert is also used to notify local media who will then broadcast any updates received on radio/TV.

Click here http://fifeps.ss19.sharpschool.com/district/district_information/emergency_closure_information for further details on all emergency closure procedures.

post_text: We are so grateful for this partnership. Thank you, Fife History Museum!
shared_text:
Julie Watts is with Pat Reed and Julie Watts.
November 22, 2019 at 3:48 PM Â·

The Fife History Museum had the honor of hosting Native American Heritage Week! Surprise Lake Middle School 7th graders toured the Burke Museum Exhibit at the Dacca Barn, and heard Native American Storytellers Roger Fernandez and Solana Booth over in the Museum. They also made Native American crafts, learned about lahars on the museum's new 3D Mt. Rainier model, learned the history of Dacca Park, and retired FHS and SLMS librarian Pat Reed taught students about the history of 7th grade in Fife. Thank you Martha Sherman, Native American Education Coordinator for Fife Schools, for allowing us to share in this awe inspiring event this year!

post_text:
Our Director of Transportation, Damian Jenkins, informed our staff this morning that for the 27th consecutive year our entire transportation fleet passed state inspection at 100%!

From Mrs. Jenkins, "Special thanks to our mechanics Nick Gratzer and Tim Barnett for keeping our fleet in excellent condition. Because of your high standards our students, staff, and parents are kept safe. Thank you Eric Rindfleisch for helping Nick and Tim throughout the inspection. Fife School District's mechanics are second to none!!!!!" We couldn't agree more!

As part of Native American Heritage Month, Coordinator of Indian Education Martha Sherman, has created a cultural showcase at our district office.

All Surprise Lake Middle School 7th grade students have had an opportunity to visit the showcase where they can view exhibits, make a necklace, and hear from storyteller and author, Sondra Segundo.

The showcase is open to the public through tomorrow. Stop by anytime between 9 AM - 5:00 PM!

Special thanks to Puyallup Tribe of Indians for the financial support of this program!

At tonight's School Board Meeting, Discovery Primary teachers Saundra Westlund and Katy Ferguson - along with a few of their 1st grade students - invited our school board members to experience a Morning Meeting. Morning Meetings are held daily in each classroom at Discovery Primary School.

These daily rituals are just one part of their school's efforts to teach empathy, de-escalation of stress, and belonging so that each child is ready to learn and knows that he/she is loved.

We are so proud of the sixty seven multilingual students who registered to take an optional world language proficiency assessment. Depending on their proficiency level these students can earn up to four world language credits!

In addition to English these students speak Russian, Spanish, Tagalog, Korean, Lao, Romanian, Samoan, Ukrainian, Vietnamese, ASL, or Marshallese.

For further information about this opportunity for multilingual students in Grades 8-12, please visit the link below!

post_text:
Did you receive your ballot?

Some Pierce County voters might be getting their ballots late, after a glitch caused nearly 7,000 ballots across the state from being sent. This may include voters in the Fife School District. We are asking voters to consider a capital bond and a levy renewal on the Feb. 13 ballot.

If you have not received your ballot yet, it should arrive by the end of the week. If you have lost or misplaced your ballot, you can visit: http://www.co.pierce.wa.us/FormCenter/Auditor-7/Replacement-Ballot-Request-Form-186

Link to news story with more info:

http://nwnewsnetwork.org/post/nearly-7000-washington-voters-will-get-last-minute-ballots-due-motor-voter-error

Here's a helpful video from State Superintendent Chris Reykdal explaining the need for local school levies.

In Fife, renewing our levy continues the funding support of these items:
- Special education, remediation, and English as a Second Language programs
- Additional certificated and classified personnel
- Professional development for teachers and instructional assistants
- Programs to challenge students such as gifted and advanced placement
- Textbooks and other instructional materials
- Transportation services
- Athletics and other extracurricular activities such as drama and music

For further information visit: https://sites.google.com/fifeschools.com/levyinfo/home
#ThisIsTheTimeThisIsThePlace

Mrs. Westlund received a personalized plaque from Trophies2Go, a $100 gift card to Daniel's Broiler Prime Steaks & Chops, and will be treated to a makeover at Blanc 'n Schwartz Salon! All students received a goodie bag of surprises to celebrate their teacher.

Special Olympics Washington
February 20, 2017 at 11:00 AM Â·

Fife Police Officer Patrick Gilbert is a prime example of selflessness. He works as a School Resource Officer for Fife High School, coaches football, is involved in his community, and in his "spare" time dedicates his energy to advocating for people with Intellectual Disabilities.

Last year he organized the first ever Hoopin' 4 Heroes basketball game, which saw first responders play against Fife High School employees- and helped to raise $5,000 dollars!

This year he once again pushed the envelope and Super Plunged in Seattle! You can find him next at Fife Highschool's 2nd Annual Hoopin for Heroes or at the Tacoma Polar Plunge this Saturday.#PledgePlungeParty

post_text: We are very proud to share the news that our former superintendent, Dr. Steve McCammon has recently been named COO of the Schlechty Center. Congratulations, Dr. McCammon! #togetherweareFIFE
shared_text:
Schlechty Center
October 31, 2016 at 5:04 AM Â·

George Thompson, Schlechty Center president and board chair, is pleased to announce that Steve McCammon has been named the Centerâ€™s chief operating officer. According to Thompson, this is an important move for the future of the Center, especially as it approaches its significant thirtieth anniversary.

Steve McCammon has served as a senior associate with the Center since 2013. Prior to that, he was superintendent in Fife Public Schools in Tacoma, Washington. Under Steveâ€™s leadership, Fife became one of the longest-participating districts in the Schlechty Centerâ€™s Standard-Bearer School District Network. Steve is enthusiastic about his work, and those he works with have respect and admiration for him, including the board and staff of the Schlechty Center.

Congratulations to Mrs. Gore, Alice V. Hedden Elementary Second Grade Teacher, for being this week's STAR 101.5 Teacher of the Week!

Mrs. Gore received a $101.50 classroom scholarship and $100 Visa gift card from Sound Credit Union, a personalized plaque from Trophies2Go, and a makeover from Blanc 'n Schwartz Salon in Kent. Plus a $50 gift card to Half Price Books.

Her students were treated to a classroom party with prizes from Dairy Farmers of Washington, KOMO 4, and STAR 101.5! Plus, a party appearance from the Dairy Farmers of Washington Dairy Ambassador!

Be sure to check out Mrs. Gore and her class on KOMO News tomorrow at 4 PM!!

It was a momentus occasion as our very first cohort of CJH AVID students and their families joined us for a signing ceremony. It's hard to convey how exciting it is to begin this program with this wonderful group of incoming freshman, but we can hardly wait to experience their success this next year and the years to come! Congratulations!!!
